<td width="100%" height="100%" align="left" valign="top"><table width="95%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="center"><tr><td colspan="3"><b><font color="#666666">Monday December 16, 2002</font></b><img src="images/date.gif" height="2" width="175"></td></tr><tr><td width="5%">&nbsp;</td><td width="90%"><p><font color="#0000CC" size="1">Posted by Thott</font> <br>
<b><font color="#000000">Elemental Fun</font></b><br>
Plane of Air contains everyone's favorite encounter type: blowable
spawns.&nbsp; Something spawns, we flub it up, and poof, it's
gone for a week.&nbsp; This is such an incredibly good idea that I'm
amazed it isn't used more in real life.
<p>
Why don't malls poof when I can't find a parking space?&nbsp; Thousands
of shoppers, wandering around a massive crater, mumbling about respawn
times - that's the Christmas spirit!&nbsp; Serves them right for not
having enough parking.
<p>
Why don't stadiums poof when a football team fumbles?&nbsp; That'd
certainly add excitement to the game.&nbsp; Maybe put some nitro glycerine
in the ball too, for a chuckle.&nbsp; I bet ratings would improve.
<p>
Airplanes that run out of drinks, another poofing opportunity.&nbsp;
If government mandated, it could be part of the Parachute Industry
Aid Package.
<p>
Plane of Water uses this same technique (no, I don't mean parachutes,
nor is there a lack of something to drink).&nbsp;
There's an event there, THE event there as best I can tell,
that sets off (and poofs afterwards) just by walking nearby, sort of
like having hospitals disappear when someone in town coughs.&nbsp; One-legged
veterans are probably nodding their heads right now, fully familiar with
the concept of things poofing just by walking by.
<p>
But these are the things we work to overcome!&nbsp; Sure we're sad we
can't try again, but at least we're getting an awful lot of loot for
our trouble.&nbsp; The mall is gone, but when it comes back, you'll love
the prices!
<p>
<center>Plane of Air</center>
<center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Plane_of_Air.jpg"></center>
<p>
It's amazing where mobs can end up, when the geometry is just right.&nbsp; This situation is very %T.
<p>
<center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Symbol_of_the_Swirling_Maelstrom.jpg"></center>
<p>
<center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Pherlondien_Clawpike_corpse.jpg"></center>
  <center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Band_of_Fortitude.jpg"></center>
<center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Muzlakh_the_Chosen_corpse.jpg"></center>
  <center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Elemental_Chain_Bracelet_Pattern.jpg"></center>
<p>
Here's a repeat drop, that was stealth upgraded last patch.&nbsp; Flagged twinks, rejoice!&nbsp; Actually pretty much <i>every</i> drop is a repeat drop.&nbsp; There isn't much depth to the loot tables.&nbsp; Is this good or bad?&nbsp; It's hard to say.&nbsp; Think "<a href="/items.cgi?item=663"><font color="000000">Torque of the Wurmlord</font></a>" and you'll see what I mean.
<p>
<center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Crystal_Tipped_Onyxwood_Staff.jpg"></center>
<p>
From Melernil Faal`armanna (Hi kids, can you say Melernil Faal`armanna?&nbsp; Me either.):
<p>
  <center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Resplendent_Epaulets.jpg"></center>
  <center><img src="/scrapbook/2002-12-16/Puresteel_Mantle.jpg"></center>
